entry.title: [Product excellence] Fix misalignment issue in SE Settings page
entry.content:
Please check b/317141209 for screenshots:

- Comment #2: status quo - misalignment with higher zoom levels

- Comment #3: before (more status quo screenshots) and after the CL



**The problem**



Status quo before the CL uses flex layout per row, which can't guarantee

that header row and other rows will have the same horizontal spacing.



The issue is not as obvious when you no zoom is applied

(https://screenshot.googleplex.com/C9kZ4BkHQfwXidD), because the

column with the controls size similar to the controls shown, so it's not

as noticeable even if you get a few pixels difference. However, when you

apply zoom, you see the header for the second column very misaligned

with the rest of the table.



The problem became much more obvious when we changed the controls for

site search created by policy. Rows on the same table can now have

different controls on the last column, completely breaking alignment

between data rows (https://screenshot.googleplex.com/7oygw7uu6ysLnz9).



**The solution**



We are fixing it by making splitting each table row into two sections:

- Assume table has always 3 columns:

- "name"

- "shortcut" or "url"

- "controls"

- Split columns into two groups:

- First column for "name" is its own group and takes 33% of horizontal

space

- Second group contains the last two columns and takes 66% of

horizontal space

- Second group uses flex layout to align second column on the left and

third column on the right



The solution is not resilient to adding a 4th column to the table, but

I think that's reasonable compromise:

- We have not added columns to that table for many years, there is no

obvious reason why we would do that now

- Status quo is also not resilient, and a new column would simply make

the problem worse than it is today

entry.title: WebUI: Fix cr-slider ripples going away on every keydown
entry.content:
cr-slider uses a paper-ripple to indicate focus has moved onto it,

but the paper-ripple goes away as soon as you interact with the slider

using the keyboard even if focus remains on the slider. This is

caused by paper-ripple removing any existing ripples whenever its

`showAndHoldDown` method is called [1].



This CL adds a check to see if it the ripple is already shown before

calling `showAndHoldDown`.

entry.title: [iOS] Show download progress for Save to Drive
entry.content:
This CL updates Download manager UI code to behave differently when the

current download task has been "added" to Save to Drive.

1. The Download manager view displays a Drive icon when the downloaded

file destination is Drive, and it displays the user email of the

destination Drive account. The progress indicator shows 50% when the

download part is finished, since the upload part i.e. the remaining

50% has yet to be performed.

2. The Download manager state, which used to map almost perfectly to

the current download task's state, now differs upon completion of the

download task: if the downloaded file will be saved to Drive, then

the Download manager state stays "in progress" as long as the upload

is not complete. This means the UI stays stuck "in progress" at 50%

when the download finishes, in the Drive case.

3. The downloaded file is not moved to the "Downloads" folder on local

storage if the downloaded file will be saved to Drive.



Bug: 1495353

entry.title: [iOS] Add download task to Save to Drive when identity selected
entry.content:
This CL adds a `DriveTabHelper` to manage Save to Drive tab-scoped state

i.e. if a `DownloadTask` is received through AddDownloadToSaveToDrive()

1 - memorises the task, what `SystemIdentity` will be used to save the

downloaded file to Drive, etc.

2 - observes the `DownloadTask` and uploads the downloaded file using

the Drive service upon completion of the task (that uploading part comes

in a later change).



A `DownloadTask` is sent to the tab helper by the SaveToDriveMediator

when an identity is selected through the Save to Drive UI.

entry.title: [iOS] Start download task when Save to Drive identity selected
entry.content:
This CL makes the DownloadManagerTabHelper call

- (void)downloadManagerTabHelper:(DownloadManagerTabHelper*)tabHelper

didAddDownloadToSaveToDrive:(web::DownloadTask*)download;

on its delegate when a DownloadTask has been "added" to Save to Drive.



For context, when a user has selected an identity through the Save to

Drive UI, two things should happen as a result:

1. The DownloadTask which was used to start the Save to Drive UI should

be registered/added to the DriveTabHelper.

2. The DownloadTask should be started. Since this operation is usually

performed by the DownloadManagerCoordinator, DownloadManagerTabHelper

is asking the coordinator to start the DownloadTask through its

`delegate_` interface.

This CL implements step 2.

completely to CreateInferredLabels. This CL achieves that by:

changed. This is not a problem but an improvement, basically we favour

entry.title: Settings: Restamp basic page so that prefs subproperty changes propagate
entry.content:
https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/5014869 fixed

an issue with the logic to show the settings basicPage. As a result the

dom-if for basicPage is now false when the current route is not set to

a route in the basic page (e.g. chrome://settings/reset).



Due to the way Polymer data bindings work inside dom-ifs, this meant

that prefs subproperty changes no longer triggered observers to fire,

so when settings like the theme were reset from

chrome://settings/reset, these changes were not correctly reflected in

the DOM even after the basic page dom-if flipped back to true (e.g.

after navigating to the appearance settings).



See https://github.com/Polymer/polymer/issues/4818 for additional

context on this Polymer behavior.



Fixing by using a restamp on the dom-if to force a rerender when it

changes from false to true.

entry.title: [omnibox][ml] Refactor `AutocompleteController`
entry.content:
go/autocomplete-controller-refactor has some details on the refactor

plan.



This is part 5 of the refactor.



- Split `UpdateResult()` into helpers. E.g. `AggregateNewMatches()`. The

goal is readers can look at `UpdateResult()` and get a outline of what

it does without having to scroll through code. This call hierarchy is

a bit flatter than before; e.g. helper 1 doesn't call helper 2 which

then calls helper 3.



- Remove `done_` and `sync_pass_done_` internal states. Before, it was

difficult to know what each `AutocompleteController()` method would

do, because their behaviors depended both on the params passed in and

the controllers internal state. So a reader would have to backstep to

figure out what the internal state was for each call path. Now, the

behavior of `UpdateResult()` & `DelayedNotifyChanged()` depend on

their parameters only. `done_` and `sync_pass_done_` were also unclear

because the former refers to the providers being done but not the

controller, whereas the latter refers to the controller being done.



- Add `last_update_type_` field. We still need internal state because

other objects need to know what autocomplete state the controller is

in. But it's not used internally by the controller itself (see above

bullet).



- Centralize some logic into `UpdateResult()`. Specifically, the stop &

expire timers are now started and stopped here instead of being

manipulated throughout the class. Also centralized here is determining

whether to run an immediate or delayed notification.



- Add extensive tests. Autocompletion is pretty nuanced; it

conditionally transfers old matches, debounces, runs expire & stop

timers, ML reranks, or preserves the default match. None of this

behavior was tested, despite how critical they were. This CL adds

extensive tests.



- Update `AutocompleteControllerMetrics` to look at `last_update_type_`

instead of the now removed `done_` and `sync_pass_done_`. It becomes a

bit simpler too.



- Update `AutocompleteControllerMetrics` tests to actually run the

controller to make sure the integration works. E.g., before, tests

would call `metrics.X(); metrics.Y()` and verify the correct metrics

were recorded. Now, the tests call `controller.A()` and verify `A()`

actually calls `X()` and `Y()` and the correct metrics are recorded.



Low-Coverage-Reason: OTHER This CL adds tests to previously untested

code. The coverage checker is looking at an iOS file that this CL

touched but is not the focus of this CL. And I'm unsure if the coverage

checker works with iOS files?

entry.title: Reland "[sidepanelpinning] Make button check anchor count when made visible."
entry.content:
This fixes the test failure by moving the SetHighlighted update back

to VisibilityChanged(). The issue was caused by SetState being called

in Button::ViewHierarchyChanged().



This is a reland of commit 84550853e3ad44bdaa9a1beca41e5fbe93db2881



Original change's description:

> [sidepanelpinning] Make button check anchor count when made visible.

>

> This issue is exposed when we add the anchor highlight before the button

> has been made visible due to animations. This change checks the buttons

> anchor count if visibility changes to true to update the highlight

> accordingly.

>

> This also fixes another bug where |anchor_count_| is not respected when

> a drag finishes.
